    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-02-10T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-02-10T11:00:00-05:00" n="292"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d292">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/4083: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at Shanghai (<persName corresp="#p_CES1" type="to"
                            >Cunningham</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-10T11:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 10, 1932—11 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>10. Your 27, February 10, 4 p.m. The Department approves a reply similar to the
                    tentative draft which you have submitted. For your consideration the Department
                    suggests that in Paragraph 2, after the words “between China and Japan”, the
                    note should read “but it must continue to hold the Governments and authorities
                    of each of the disputants responsible for any loss or damage which may be
                    inflicted by any armed forces or any agencies thereof to American lives and
                    property as a result of such dispute”.</p>
                <p>Repeat to Nanking and inform Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
